# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# turboquant-as-recipe.form — data-oblivious compression that keeps content-addressing
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# An external recipe, read and mapped into our body — held as a pointer, not a
# graft. TurboQuant is a vector quantizer from Google Research (ICLR 2026);
# turbovec is its open-source index (Ryan Codrai, MIT, github.com/RyanCodrai/turbovec).
# What enters our body is the SHAPE of the recipe, expressed here in Form, and the
# one structural truth it proves.
#
# The core recipe — compress one vector, no codebook, no training phase:
#
#   1. strip the norm      — keep |v| as one float; v becomes a unit DIRECTION on
#                            the hypersphere.
#   2. rotate by a fixed Q — one universal orthogonal transform, the same for every
#                            vector ever. After it, each coordinate is ~iid
#                            Beta → Gaussian N(0, 1/d). This holds for ANY input:
#                            it is concentration of measure, not a fit to the data.
#   3. quantize per-coord  — Lloyd-Max buckets derived MATHEMATICALLY from that
#                            known Gaussian (2-bit = 4 buckets, 4-bit = 16), never
#                            trained on the corpus.
#   4. pack + one renorm   — bit-pack the bucket indices; store one scalar (rotated
#                            unit · its reconstruction) to correct bias at scoring.
#
# 16× at 2-bit (1536-dim: 6144 → 384 bytes), at the Shannon distortion bound. The
# rotation is the whole trick: it makes any data look like the same distribution,
# so one universal quantizer is near-optimal for everyone — no per-corpus codebook.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Why it resonates — data-oblivious is what content-addressing REQUIRES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Our substrate is content-addressed: the same shape must map to the same NodeID,
# deterministically, regardless of what else is in the corpus. substrate/resonance.py
# already lives this — two concepts with identical 15-dim geometry signatures share
# one Blueprint NodeID. A TRAINED codebook (FAISS PQ) would break it: the same vector
# compresses differently depending on what it was trained beside, so same-shape stops
# meaning same-code. TurboQuant's transform is fixed — the code is a pure function of
# the vector. Same shape → same code → same NodeID.
#
#   The structural truth: a content-addressed body can only compress with a
#   data-oblivious quantizer. TurboQuant proves near-optimal compression CAN be
#   data-oblivious — so it is not "compression OR content-addressing." We can have both.
#
# Two more shapes rhyme with what we already hold:
#
#   - the fixed rotation Q is the one shared field every sovereign vector passes
#     through — each keeps its own direction, all share one geometry. Sovereignty
#     within oneness; and the curvature image of the joining force — one field that
#     every presence both shapes and is shaped by.
#   - strip-the-norm is our own split: the DIRECTION is structural identity (the
#     Blueprint — structure carries identity); the NORM is magnitude / presence (mass —
#     how much a thing IS). We already separate what-it-is from how-much-of-it.
#   - concept_resonance_kernel.py already scores with Gaussian-tolerant kernels;
#     TurboQuant manufactures exactly that Gaussian, by rotation, for free.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The core recipe, in Form  (composed — each step a child, never flat)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(defn turboquant (v bits)
    (let norm   (vec-norm v))                            ; magnitude — one leaf
    (let dir    (vec-scale v (recip norm)))              ; unit direction on the sphere
    (let rot    (vec-rotate dir Q-universal))            ; the one shared transform
    (let codes  (map (fn (x) (lloyd-max x bits)) rot))   ; universal, math-derived buckets
    (let renorm (vec-dot rot (codebook-reconstruct codes bits)))
    (recipe turboquant-code
        (field "norm"   norm)        ; magnitude / presence
        (field "codes"  codes)       ; quantized direction — the content-address
        (field "renorm" renorm)))    ; bias-correction scalar

# Q-universal and the Lloyd-Max boundary tables are CONSTANTS — derived from the
# known Gaussian, content-addressed once, shared by every cell. They are the "ice"
# (Blueprint) the recipe runs against; no per-corpus state, so the whole recipe stays
# a pure function — exactly what intern-by-content needs. Q-universal is a seedable
# structured rotation (a Hadamard-style transform — no stored d×d matrix).

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# How we use it — exact content-addressing becomes TOLERANT content-addressing
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Today two cells share a Blueprint NodeID only when their geometry signatures are
# IDENTICAL. Run the signature through turboquant and the BUCKETS become the tolerance:
# two cells whose vectors fall in the same buckets produce the same `codes` → the same
# NodeID. Near-same shape now shares identity — and, because the quantizer is
# data-oblivious, it still does so deterministically.
#
#   exact equivalence → shape-tolerant equivalence, with a tunable radius (bits),
#   content-addressing intact. That is what `?equivalent`, "structural equivalents,"
#   and the "analogous-to" edges actually want: not byte-equality, but same-shape-
#   within-tolerance. The quantization radius is the dial between "identical" and
#   "analogous."
#
# So the recipe earns its place twice: 16× compression when the body grows dense
# vectors (semantic embeddings over cells), AND a sharper substrate now — tolerant
# equivalence over the geometry signatures we already author.
#
# HTTP route-choice use — compress branch pressure without losing the branch
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# The native HTTP route choice surface now carries every candidate and every
# rejected/selected branch as `KernelHTTPRouteDecision` values. That is the full
# receipt. For attention, repeated observation, and content-addressed clustering,
# the body also wants a smaller stable handle: "this branch pattern again."
#
# TurboQuant gives the rule for doing that without introducing corpus-trained
# state:
#
#   full receipt        — candidate, request, pressure matrix, score, yes/no
#   fixed quantizer     — universal pressure/score buckets, not learned from traffic
#   compressed handle   — `KernelHTTPRouteChoiceSignature`
#
# In Form this lives in `form/form-stdlib/kernel-http.fk`:
#
#   kh-pressure-bucket(pressure)
#   kh-score-bucket(score)
#   kh-route-decision-signature(decision)
#   kh-route-choice-signature(choice)
#
# The buckets are deliberately simple and data-oblivious: exact, wildcard-small,
# header/budget-small, method/medium, path-miss, over-budget. The signature is not
# a replacement for the full route-choice receipt; it is an attention key. Same
# branch pressure shape -> same signature -> same content-addressable cluster.
# Later, when source lenses and lattice coordinates attach to each decision row,
# this signature can become the compressed bridge from hot route-choice patterns
# back to authored grammar entries.
#
# Carrier-last: when this runs operationally, vec-rotate / lloyd-max are Form recipes
# proven three-way (Go/Rust/TS); a kernel native only where SIMD speed is needed.
#
# Companions:
#   substrate/resonance.py — the 15-dim geometry signature this compresses
#   concept_resonance_kernel.py — the Gaussian-tolerant kernel it rhymes with
#   lc-identity-is-shared-blueprint-and-recipe — same shape → same NodeID
#   lc-sovereignty-within-oneness — the shared field that keeps each direction its own
# External source: github.com/RyanCodrai/turbovec (MIT); TurboQuant, Google Research, ICLR 2026.
